eanings":["English:","habitational name from any of the three places called Sudbury (Derbyshire, Middlesex, Suffolk) or from Sudborough (Northamptonshire), all of which are named with Old English <i>sūth</i> ‘south, southern’ + <i>burg</i> ‘fortified place’ or ‘manor’.","habitational name from Chipping, Little, or Old Sodbury (Gloucestershire). The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Soppa</i> (genitive <i>Soppan</i>) + Old English <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’. This surname does not appear to have survived unless   Sobey   is an altered form of it, but this is quite uncertain."],"variants":[{"name":"Sadberry","meanings":["Altered form of English   Sudbury  . Compare   Sedberry  ."]},{"name":"Sudberry","meanings":["English: variant of   Sudbury  . This form of the name has now died out in Britain."]},{"name":"Sidbury","meanings":["English: variant of   Sudbury  . Compare   Sadberry  ."]},{"name":"Sobey","meanings":["English (Cornwall and Devon): perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Soby</i>, of uncertain origin. It could derive from the rare Old French name <i>Sob(b)o</i>, a pet form of ancient Germanic names like <i>Sudbald</i> and <i>Sudbert</i> (composed of the elements <i>sud-</i> ‘south’ + <i>-bald</i> ‘bold’ and <i>-bert</i> ‘bright’). A habitational name from a shortened form of <i>Sobbery</i>, a Middle English form of Sodbury, Gloucestershire (see   Sudbury  ), is also formally possible but no evidence has been found that definitely links the two names. This surname is found in Cornwall from the late 13th century."]}]},{"name":"Isabella","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."],"variants":[{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently